05907nam a22009615i 9780691211985DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020022663  a97806912119857 a10.1515/97806912119852doi  a(DE-B1597)554878  a(OCoLC)1176322094  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aBL624 7aREL0620002bisacsh04a202/.1172231 aLuhrmann, T.M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow God Becomes Real :bKindling the Presence of Invisible Others /cT.M. Luhrmann. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b3 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1 The Faith Frame -- t2 Making Paracosms -- t3 Talent and Training -- t4 How the Mind Matters -- t5 Evidence for the Way Gods and Spirits Respond -- t6 Why Prayer Works -- t7 A God Who Responds -- tAcknowledgments -- tGeneral Notes on Methods -- tBibliographic Essays and Notes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe hard work required to make god real, how it changes the people who do it, and why it helps explain the enduring power of faithHow do gods and spirits come to feel vividly real to people-as if they were standing right next to them? Humans tend to see supernatural agents everywhere, as the cognitive science of religion has shown. But it isn't easy to maintain a sense that there are invisible spirits who care about you. In How God Becomes Real, acclaimed anthropologist and scholar of religion T. M. Luhrmann argues that people must work incredibly hard to make gods real and that this effort-by changing the people who do it and giving them the benefits they seek from invisible others-helps to explain the enduring power of faith.Drawing on ethnographic studies of evangelical Christians, pagans, magicians, Zoroastrians, Black Catholics, Santeria initiates, and newly orthodox Jews, Luhrmann notes that none of these people behave as if gods and spirits are simply there. Rather, these worshippers make strenuous efforts to create a world in which invisible others matter and can become intensely present and real. The faithful accomplish this through detailed stories, absorption, the cultivation of inner senses, belief in a porous mind, strong sensory experiences, prayer, and other practices. Along the way, Luhrmann shows why faith is harder than belief, why prayer is a metacognitive activity like therapy, why becoming religious is like getting engrossed in a book, and much more.A fascinating account of why religious practices are more powerful than religious beliefs, How God Becomes Real suggests that faith is resilient not because it provides intuitions about gods and spirits-but because it changes the faithful in profound ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPresence of God. 0aSpirituality. 7aRELIGION / Spirituality.2bisacsh  aGood Parsi.  aOf Two Minds.  aOur Most Troubling Madness.  aPersuasion of the Witch's Craft.  aanthropology of mind.  aanthropology of religion.  aethnography.  afeeling the presence of god.  ahow prayer works.  apsychological anthropologist.  apsychological anthropology.  apsychology of prayer.  apsychology of religious experience.  apsychology of seeing god.  aunderstanding religious experience.  aunderstanding religious practice.  awhat happens to religious worshippers.  awhy prayer works.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G